en.csharp_lesson1_ex10_slide2_content:
# Using Logical Operators

Example 1: Both conditions must be met (and)
```csharp
if (score >= 80 && attendance >= 90)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Excellent!");
}
```
→ Displays "Excellent!" only when score is 80+ AND attendance is 90+

Example 2: Either must be met (or)
```csharp
if (day == "Saturday" || day == "Sunday")
{
    Console.WriteLine("Day off");
}
```
→ Displays "Day off" if Saturday OR Sunday

Key Points:
- `&&` - whole thing is true only if both are true
- `||` - whole thing is true if either one is true

en.csharp_lesson3_ex10_slide2_content:
# Clearly Define Scope with { }

In older C#, wrapping `using` in a `{ }` block was the standard syntax. It still works.

Block Syntax (Old Style):
```csharp
using (var file = new StreamReader("file.txt")) {
    var content = file.ReadToEnd();
    // Use file inside here
}  // Dispose when leaving }
```

Using Declaration (New Style):
```csharp
using var file = new StreamReader("file.txt");
var content = file.ReadToEnd();
// Dispose at end of method
```

Difference:
- Old style: Dispose when leaving `{ }`
- New style: Dispose at method end

The new syntax is simpler, but both are correct!

